document.title: STRANDS AND STANDARDS FOOD AND NUTRITION

55E01E6D37FB4CB58A4A3C20FC9C3834.description: Oils – Choose vegetable oils and naturally occurring oils in foods like seafood and nuts.

FF95606F9E6D4FDFBEC0B50E02C0BE89.description: Dairy—Choose a variety of dairy products. Check for added sugars in low fat dairy products.

E9157E8B6A8149B5B7CEBEBB7F15BE51.description:
Fruit—Choose whole or cut-up fruits more often than fruit juice. Make half your plate fruits and
vegetables.

AE6680AC9C9A4277B388356F4490024D.description:
Vegetable—Choose a variety including fresh, frozen, canned, or dried. Eat more red, orange, and
dark green vegetables.

AE1EF8EF54C045F58ADDD5BD144257C4.description:
Protein—Choose a variety of foods from complete and incomplete protein sources. Keep portions
small and lean.

75BF2130F57F4A3891275D7B719D6E6E.description: Grains—Choose 100% whole grain. Make at least half of the grains consumed whole grain.

03488387972F46559B0B9B58B7E16918.description: Identify the characteristics of MyPlate. “Make every bite count.”

03C3CE5F29BB43499DAE3C867B3C5BA3.description: Children and teens should be physically active for at least 60 minutes every day.

4241DB8E18214ABBA55BFEA44EF5DDB8.description: Include physical activity as part of a healthy lifestyle.

3506E71B51424444AD444B8F0E4BD043.description:
Reduce empty-calorie foods. Empty-calorie foods are those that are high in calories, sodium, and
saturated fats with very little nutrient value.

2B6B45E88559405E8303687CE6AA455B.description: Limit calories from added sugars and saturated fats, and reduce sodium intake.

7E06874EDA3A4E5DACDF7E58998D9EE1.description: No more than 10% should be from saturated fats.

49697FECA6B9448399B5ABF8EA1198B6.description: No more than 30% lipids—9 calories per gram.

887A9AF5D4A840EBBCF7B6695DCB5572.description:
To meet nutrient needs within calorie limits, choose a variety of nutrient-dense foods across and
within all food groups in recommended amounts.

AE651B91FF8B42D987E1362B37801B5D.description: Nutrient-dense foods provide vitamins, minerals, and other beneficial substances with relativelyfew calories.

8CA7874166E648DB966034348A808436.description:
Focus on variety, nutrient density, and portion sizes as defined by a nutrition facts label. Nutrition
facts labels are based on a 2,000-calorie diet.

0A09FEDB89C24DDEB742EE72394563B1.description:
Choose a healthy eating pattern at an appropriate calorie level to help achieve and maintain a
healthy body weight, support nutrient adequacy, and reduce the risk of disease.

8655BB18F4B04433A10EEE7FE0783397.description: Follow a healthy eating pattern across the lifespan.

54A965D1A765499594213DE3DC3C0DFE.description: Students will explore healthy nutrition guidelines.

Prevent enzymatic browning of fresh produce by covering with liquid or dipping in an ascorbic acid
liquid.

Select fresh produce that is firm, free from decay, crisp, smooth, dense (heavy for size), free from
bruises and have good color.

9F420DAD37BA404B9258BF7ABF8CC32C.description: Identify how to select fresh produce.

6225AE347D11421AB05E96C8B0DD3699.description:
Electrolyte balance and carbohydrate replacement may needed for moderate to high-intensity
activities lasting longer than 60 minutes.

44B30ECB57514B03983BBC54F213BF01.description:
Athletes or anyone physically active needs to drink higher quantities of water, particularly in hot
environments (heat of the day).

8076F959A6BD4B7EA508B7498CC66A4E.description: 64 fl. oz. of water is recommended daily.

8D4F885B1F57476682D3FDDBF9D3AA9D.description: Water is the most important of all the essential nutrients.

C1436BD2772849888A0E7063CA97A826.description: Urine should be a pale yellow color. Darker urine is another indication of dehydration.

7ED81D783B4442EE91F4D81745C2A7D3.description: Thirst is an indicator of dehydration.

238791B7496943B18D6CAC18916D2AC2.description: Dehydration occurs from lack of water.

9C4256E20C1F43BB9FAE36ADD220E273.description:
Potassium(Electrolytes)Helps maintain a regular heartbeat. Prevents muscle cramps. Sources
include bananas, potatoes, and nuts.

5EF3112118234157BBC026640C68C939.description:
Sodium(Electrolytes)Helps maintain the fluid balance and blood pressure in the body. Deficiency is
not generally a concern, unless over-hydrating. Sources include salt and processed foods.

A9B9A41108A24F168E3BF49363F006CD.description:
Electrolytes: Minerals that help maintain fluid balance in the body, maintain the heartbeat and help
muscle and nerve action.

D64FE87AF5024A588849695688D71D34.description:
Iron(Micro/Trace mineral): Helps to form the hemoglobin in red blood cells which carry oxygen
throughout the body. Prevents anemia. Sources include red meat, spinach, black beans and dried
fruit.

BE03B9B9DD28415A8BF234F7D06B6EA7.description: Micro/Trace Mineral: Usually needed in small amounts but are critical to health.

5FC68E3DDE9749708FFBA1B2CB237689.description:
Calcium(Macro mineral): Builds strong bones and teeth. Calcium deficiency causes bones to
become weak this is called osteoporosis. Good sources are found in dairy products.

635A1C70086D4517B5F3FD2B18E90D52.description: Macro Mineral: Are needed in greater quantities in the body.

FB1BB258337D4F2D85CB867C3116D37D.description: Identify select minerals, their food sources, functions and deficiencies in the body.

98A55C489B3643198AAD177CFFC60ACA.description: Vitamin E: Protects membranes of white and red blood cells.

B75864D44AFA4738A0AE71434FC3C510.description: Vitamin K: Helps blood clot properly.

697D9D9E90DE487AA0D77C796CB29BF1.description:
Vitamin D: Works with the body to build and maintain healthy bones and teeth. Prevents bonesoftening and loss. Sources include milk products. Manufactured by the body with exposure to
sunlight.

0DFD1B1474854EBC86DCD246F4F6D08E.description:
Vitamin A: Maintains normal vision and immune system. Prevents night blindness. Sources: Orange
and dark green vegetables.

F3BFFC6267AA408BA6A0BA46FA7EE259.description:
Folate or Vitamin B9 is one of the B Vitamins. Folate helps tissue to grow and cells to work. Folate
reduces the risk of neural tube birth defects. Sources include legumes, dark leafy greens,citrus, and
eggs.

8F65964A29A54F86AA43F70E96033819.description:
Vitamin C: Helps to form collagen which holds the cells together and aids in healing. Prevents
scurvy. Sources include citrus, strawberries, broccoli and peppers.

B8A19604AAE64AE3985312A7D6F4C5AD.description: Identify select vitamins, their food sources, functions and deficiencies in the body.

391F886100584369B5065542CDF3746D.description: Students will identify the sources and functions of select vitamins, minerals and water and apply appropriate food preparation techniques to foods high in these nutrients.

LDL cholesterol is “bad” cholesterol because if too much LDL cholesterol is circulating in the- blood
stream, it can be deposited in the arteries and increase the chance of heart disease or stroke.

FA30774F9407440F92511814BDCC20C3.description:
HDL cholesterol is “good” cholesterol because it transports excess cholesterol found in the blood
stream back to the liver.

A97E5EC9FC044CD4BAC88C337361F55D.description:

is found in animal tissues, but is never present in plants.

0D0A24159A794EFF8F251DBF9E1B934F.description: Serving food: no bare-hand contact with RTE food.

Food Preparation: clean and sanitize food contact surfaces and equipment, wash hands between task,
never place cooked food on/in a container that has previously held raw meat, poultry or seafood.

Equipment Storage: Store glasses and cups upside down on a clean, sanitized surface, and store utensils
with handles up.

8B885C40601445BF94298FF6D9993578.description: Cross-contamination is the transfer of pathogens from people, surfaces, or food to food.

The 9 major food allergens include: tree nuts, eggs, milk, soy, wheat, peanuts, fish, sesame, and
shellfish

7F2D43ED5B974A93BF2A4B20060FBBDF.description: Cross-contact is when a food item containing an allergen comes in contact with another food.

7224B104269C4245A017B1786683D285.description: As part of the cooking process.

AD71C12A779B4883B3E16BD26D0F229D.description: In the microwave. Prepare and use food immediately.

2D7DACB4516B484FA31420BD23A53B70.description:
In a sink of cold, running water or a sink/container full of cold water, change the water every 30
minutes. Prepare and use food immediately.

Time in the danger zone includes shopping, transportation, preparation, and holding for
service.

9533CE72D77B4C4895564694C23B6047.description: Foods held in the danger zone for longer than 4 hours should be thrown out.

6EB9F5DA73654D5889B8D2704F35B550.description:
Foods like milk/dairy, meat, fish, eggs, poultry, shellfish/crustaceans, baked potatoes, tofu, sprouts,
cooked rice, beans and vegetables, sliced melons or tomatoes, and lettuce are susceptible to
pathogens. These are known as TCS foods (Time/Temperature Control for Safety).

33195C1E68504B5D999F791C72C47932.description: When in doubt, throw it out.

32C3474D6F8043F8ABED59289B780389.description: Food will often look and smell normal even if unsafe.

B33D5CF7E5804C46B34E7DF7804F095E.description:
Common types of food-borne illnesses may include: Campylobacter, Clostridium Perfringens, E-coli,
Norovirus, Salmonella, Staphylococci, Hepatitis A, Botulism.

984C5FFA19F24AA1A22CF05D02A103A1.description: Common symptoms of a food-borne illness include fever, headache, nausea, vomiting and diarrhea.

36F0FBA01F9D4E4B840B49FB135F4B8C.description:
Bacteria need certain conditions to grow. FATTOM: Food, Acid, Time, Temperature, Oxygen, and
Moisture.

74BD740A13244C2A853DB6877615F39B.description: Pathogens are any bacteria, virus, parasite, or fungi that can cause illness.
